The following code customises `strong_order` for `float`, but the compiler still uses `std::strong_order`:

```
#include <compare>

// Customization for float.
// NaN is greater than any other numbers, regardless the sign bit.                                                                                     
constexpr std::strong_ordering strong_order(float a, float b) noexcept {
    if(__builtin_isnan(a))
        return __builtin_isnan(b) ? std::strong_ordering::equivalent : std::strong_ordering::greater;
    if(__builtin_isnan(b))
        return std::strong_ordering::less;
    const auto c = a <=> b;
    return c < 0 ? std::strong_ordering::less : c > 0 ? std::strong_ordering::greater : std::strong_ordering::equivalent;
}

int main() {
    using std::strong_order;
    constexpr float NEG_NAN = -std::numeric_limits<float>::quiet_NaN();
    // Expected, but error
    static_assert(std::strong_ordering::less == strong_order(3.0f, NEG_NAN));
}
```

I checked the source and believe the problem is in libstdc++-v3/libsupc++/compare (https://github.com/gcc-mirror/gcc/blob/master/libstdc%2B%2B-v3/libsupc%2B%2B/compare#L965).
The library makes its own customisation (_S_fp_cmp) and calls it before ADL branch, which means user-defined code will be ignored.

The same problem can happen for `weak_order` (https://github.com/gcc-mirror/gcc/blob/master/libstdc%2B%2B-v3/libsupc%2B%2B/compare#L1011), while `partial_order` is fine because it checks ADL at the top.

And I think the latest G++ should have the same problem as shown in the latest source.

